The HIP 65426 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HIP 65426 is a star with 1.96 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.77 times its radius. It is located 363.337784 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 0.014 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HIP 65426 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HIP 65426 system

HIP 65426 b

HIP 65426 b was discovered by the Paranal Observatory observatory using the Imaging method. The mass of HIP 65426 b is 2860.47 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HIP 65426 b is 16.814 that of Earth. At more than 10 Earth masses, HIP 65426 b is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system. At more than 50 Earth masses, HIP 65426 b is a gas giant, a planet whose mass is mostly made up of hydrogen and helium, like Jupiter and Saturn in our solar system.
